Cognitive Bridge Architecture (CBA)

A Formal Theory of Interpretable Interaction Between Humans and Superintelligent Systems

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

The emergence of Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) and superintelligent systems introduces a structural Epistemic Divergence Problem (EDP): as AI systems surpass human reasoning capabilities, their outputs become structurally incommensurable with human cognitive representation. No existing framework provides formally bounded, architecture‑agnostic guarantees on meaning preservation across this gap.

This dissertation develops the Cognitive Bridge Architecture (CBA): a multi‑layered transformation system that maps superintelligent semantic outputs into human‑actionable representations through a sequence of contractive transformations in pragmatic metric semantic spaces. The framework is grounded in inferentialist semantics (Brandom, 1994) and operationalized through an Inferential Divergence Metric defined via Jensen‑Shannon divergence over action‑outcome distributions. CBA requires only that superintelligent outputs can be embedded in a metric space — it makes no assumption about internal architecture.

The central formal contributions are:

Theorem 1 (Semantic Convergence): For an admissible CBA chain of depth n, the inferential divergence between human‑layer representations is bounded by the product of contraction factors times the original superintelligent divergence, plus a weighted sum of action‑consistency errors. This provides the first provable, explicit bound on cumulative semantic loss across a multi‑layer interpretation chain.

Theorem 2 (Collapse Detection): Under the assumption that the human confidence function is Lipschitz with respect to inferential divergence, a transformation layer that causes semantic collapse — mapping inferentially distant points to nearly identical outputs — induces a detectable lower bound on calibration error.

Theorem 3 (Existence of Admissible Chains): For any compact pragmatic semantic spaces \mathcal{S} and \mathcal{H} with h_{\mathcal{S}} \ge h_{\mathcal{H}} and for any desired contraction bound \Lambda^*\in(0,1) and error budget \mathcal{E}^*>0, there exists an admissible CBA chain of finite depth connecting them, provided each quantized cell in the construction admits a representative that preserves action‑outcome distributions up to a prescribed tolerance.

Theorem 4 (Impossibility of Lossless Bridging): No CBA chain can preserve full semantic content when \mathcal{S} has strictly greater metric entropy than \mathcal{H}. The epistemic divergence of any bridge map satisfies \mathrm{ED}(\Phi) \le \frac{h_{\mathcal{H}}}{h_{\mathcal{S}}} < 1, i.e., some meaning is necessarily lost.

Lemma 2 (Feedback Stability): Under a regularized update rule with spectral normalization, the human feedback loop converges to a bounded neighborhood of the initial configuration, preventing unbounded alignment drift.

Together these results constitute a rigorous mathematical theory of human‑superintelligence semantic bridging, with open problems stated precisely for the research community.

