2. Formal Foundations

2.1 Preliminaries and Notation

· \mathcal{S}: superintelligent semantic space; (\mathcal{S}, d_{\mathcal{S}}) its metric.
· \mathcal{H}: human cognitive space; (\mathcal{H}, d_{\mathcal{H}}) its metric.
· \mathcal{X}_k: intermediate space at layer k; (\mathcal{X}_k, d_k) its metric.
· \mathcal{A}: set of actions (finite or compact metric space).
· \mathcal{O}: set of observable outcomes (finite or measurable space).
· \mu_{\mathcal{A}}: probability measure over actions.
· P_x(\cdot\mid a): distribution over outcomes given knowledge state x and action a.
· D_{JS}(P\|Q): Jensen‑Shannon divergence (see Definition 2).
· T_k:\mathcal{X}_k\to\mathcal{X}_{k+1}: transformation at layer k.
· \alpha_k\in[0,1): semantic contraction factor of T_k.
· \epsilon_k\ge 0: action‑consistency tolerance of T_k.
· \tilde{\epsilon}_k = 2\epsilon_k: absorbed error factor.
· \Lambda = \prod_{k=0}^{n-1}\alpha_k: cumulative contraction.
· \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{X}): \delta-covering number of metric space \mathcal{X}.
· h_{\mathcal{X}}: metric entropy of \mathcal{X}, defined as \lim_{\delta\to 0}\log\mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{X}) when this limit exists.

2.2 Pragmatic Semantic Spaces

Definition 1 (Action‑Outcome Model). An action‑outcome model for a space \mathcal{X} is a measurable function P:\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{A}\to\Delta(\mathcal{O}), where \Delta(\mathcal{O}) is the set of probability distributions over outcomes. For x\in\mathcal{X} and a\in\mathcal{A}, P_x(\cdot\mid a)=P(x,a) is the predicted outcome distribution.

Definition 2 (Inferential Divergence Metric). For x,y\in\mathcal{X}, define the inferential divergence as:

d_{\mathcal{X}}(x,y)=\sqrt{\mathbb{E}_{a\sim\mu_{\mathcal{A}}}\big[ D_{JS}\big(P_x(\cdot\mid a)\,\|\,P_y(\cdot\mid a)\big) \big]},

where D_{JS}(P\|Q)=\frac12 D_{KL}(P\|\frac{P+Q}{2})+\frac12 D_{KL}(Q\|\frac{P+Q}{2}) is the Jensen‑Shannon divergence.

Proposition 1 (Metric Properties). d_{\mathcal{X}} is a true metric on the space of equivalence classes of representations that induce identical action‑outcome distributions. In particular, it satisfies:

· Non‑negativity: d_{\mathcal{X}}(x,y)\ge 0, equality iff P_x(\cdot\mid a)=P_y(\cdot\mid a) for \mu_{\mathcal{A}}-almost all a.
· Symmetry: d_{\mathcal{X}}(x,y)=d_{\mathcal{X}}(y,x).
· Triangle inequality: d_{\mathcal{X}}(x,z)\le d_{\mathcal{X}}(x,y)+d_{\mathcal{X}}(y,z).

Proof sketch. The Jensen‑Shannon divergence is a symmetric f-divergence, and its square root is known to satisfy the triangle inequality (it is a metric on probability distributions). Linearity of expectation and the monotonicity of the square root preserve the triangle inequality. ∎

Definition 3 (Pragmatic Semantic Space). A pragmatic semantic space is a pair (\mathcal{X}, d_{\mathcal{X}}) where \mathcal{X} is equipped with an action‑outcome model and d_{\mathcal{X}} is the induced inferential divergence metric. Two spaces are compatible if they share the same action distribution \mu_{\mathcal{A}}.

2.3 Epistemic Divergence Problem

Definition 4 (Epistemic Divergence of a Mapping). For a measurable map f:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{H}, define

\mathrm{ED}(f)=\sup_{\substack{s_1,s_2\in\mathcal{S}\\ d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1,s_2)>0}} \frac{d_{\mathcal{H}}(f(s_1),f(s_2))}{d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1,s_2)}.

Definition 5 (Epistemic Divergence Problem). The Epistemic Divergence Problem (EDP) states that for any mapping f with finite information capacity, \mathrm{ED}(f)<1. Moreover, when h_{\mathcal{S}}>h_{\mathcal{H}}, we have \mathrm{ED}(f)\le h_{\mathcal{H}}/h_{\mathcal{S}}<1. (See Theorem 4.)

2.4 Transformation Chains

Definition 6 (CBA Chain). A Cognitive Bridge Architecture of depth n is a sequence of compatible pragmatic semantic spaces

\mathcal{X}_0=\mathcal{S},\;\mathcal{X}_1,\;\dots,\;\mathcal{X}_n=\mathcal{H}

together with measurable transformations T_k:\mathcal{X}_k\to\mathcal{X}_{k+1} for k=0,\dots,n-1. The composed map \Phi=T_{n-1}\circ\cdots\circ T_0:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{H} is the bridge map.

Definition 7 (Semantic Contractivity). T_k is semantically contractive with factor \alpha_k\in[0,1) if for all x,y\in\mathcal{X}_k,

d_{k+1}(T_k(x),T_k(y))\le \alpha_k\,d_k(x,y).

Definition 8 (Action Consistency). T_k is \epsilon_k-action‑consistent if for every x\in\mathcal{X}_k and every a\in\mathcal{A},

D_{JS}\big(P_{T_k(x)}(\cdot\mid a)\,\|\,P_x(\cdot\mid a)\big)\le \epsilon_k.

Definition 9 (Admissible Chain). A CBA chain is admissible if:

1. Each T_k is \alpha_k-contractive for some \alpha_k\in[0,1).
2. Each T_k is \epsilon_k-action‑consistent for some \epsilon_k\ge0.
3. The cumulative contraction \Lambda=\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}\alpha_k satisfies \Lambda\le\Lambda^* for a designer‑specified threshold \Lambda^*\in(0,1).
4. The intermediate spaces satisfy monotone metric entropy: h_{\mathcal{S}}=h_{\mathcal{X}_0}\ge h_{\mathcal{X}_1}\ge\cdots\ge h_{\mathcal{X}_n}=h_{\mathcal{H}}.

2.5 Core Theorems and Proofs

Lemma 1 (Perturbed Contraction Composition). Let T:\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Y} be \alpha-contractive and \epsilon-action‑consistent. Then for all x_1,x_2\in\mathcal{X},

d_{\mathcal{Y}}(T(x_1),T(x_2))\le \alpha\,d_{\mathcal{X}}(x_1,x_2)+2\sqrt{\epsilon}.

Proof. For each i, let \hat{x}_i\in\mathcal{Y} be an ideal representative satisfying P_{\hat{x}_i}(\cdot\mid a)=P_{x_i}(\cdot\mid a) for all a (such representatives exist by the definition of pragmatic semantic space up to the metric equivalence). By action‑consistency, d_{\mathcal{Y}}(T(x_i),\hat{x}_i)\le\sqrt{\epsilon}. Then

d_{\mathcal{Y}}(T(x_1),T(x_2))\le d_{\mathcal{Y}}(T(x_1),\hat{x}_1)+d_{\mathcal{Y}}(\hat{x}_1,\hat{x}_2)+d_{\mathcal{Y}}(\hat{x}_2,T(x_2))\le \sqrt{\epsilon}+d_{\mathcal{X}}(x_1,x_2)+\sqrt{\epsilon}.

Using contractivity, the better bound is \alpha d_{\mathcal{X}}(x_1,x_2)+2\sqrt{\epsilon}. ∎

Theorem 1 (Semantic Convergence). Let \{T_k\}_{k=0}^{n-1} be an admissible CBA chain where each T_k is \alpha_k-contractive and \epsilon_k-action‑consistent. Define \tilde{\epsilon}_k=2\sqrt{\epsilon_k}. Then for any s_1,s_2\in\mathcal{S}, with h_i=\Phi(s_i),

d_{\mathcal{H}}(h_1,h_2)\le \left(\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}\alpha_k\right)d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1,s_2)+\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left(\prod_{j=k+1}^{n-1}\alpha_j\right)\tilde{\epsilon}_k.

Proof by induction. The base case n=1 follows directly from Lemma 1. Inductive step: assume the bound holds for depth n; for depth n+1 define x_k^{(i)}=T_{k-1}\circ\cdots\circ T_0(s_i). By induction,

d_n(x_n^{(1)},x_n^{(2)})\le \Lambda_n d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1,s_2)+\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left(\prod_{j=k+1}^{n-1}\alpha_j\right)\tilde{\epsilon}_k,

where \Lambda_n=\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}\alpha_k. Applying Lemma 1 to T_n yields

d_{\mathcal{H}}(h_1,h_2)\le \alpha_n d_n(x_n^{(1)},x_n^{(2)})+\tilde{\epsilon}_n.

Substituting the induction hypothesis and simplifying gives the desired formula for depth n+1. ∎

Corollary 1 (Single‑Output Bound). Fix a reference s^*\in\mathcal{S} with h^*=\Phi(s^*). Then

d_{\mathcal{H}}(\Phi(s),h^*)\le \Lambda\,d_{\mathcal{S}}(s,s^*)+\mathcal{E},

where \mathcal{E}=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\big(\prod_{j=k+1}^{n-1}\alpha_j\big)\tilde{\epsilon}_k.

Corollary 2 (Zero‑Error Limit). If all \epsilon_k=0, then d_{\mathcal{H}}(\Phi(s),h^*)\le\Lambda\,d_{\mathcal{S}}(s,s^*).

Corollary 3 (Depth‑Efficiency Tradeoff). For fixed \Lambda and total error budget, the error term \mathcal{E} is minimized when action‑consistency errors are concentrated in the earliest layers (largest k-index in the product), i.e., later layers should be more action‑consistent.

2.6 Semantic Collapse and Collapse Detection

Definition 10 (Semantic Collapse). T_k induces (\delta,\eta)-semantic collapse if there exist x,y\in\mathcal{X}_k with d_k(x,y)>\delta but d_{k+1}(T_k(x),T_k(y))\le\eta, where 0\le\eta\ll\delta.

Definition 11 (Calibration Error). For final output h=\Phi(s), the calibration error is

\mathrm{CE}(h)=\mathbb{E}_{a\sim\mu_{\mathcal{A}}}\big[|\mathrm{conf}(a\mid h)-\mathrm{acc}(a\mid h)|\big],

where \mathrm{conf}(a\mid h)\in[0,1] is the human’s confidence that action a succeeds given h, and \mathrm{acc}(a\mid h)=\mathbb{E}[P_s(\text{success}\mid a)] is the actual success probability under the original SI output s.

Theorem 2 (Collapse Detection). Assume the human confidence function c:\Delta(\mathcal{O})\to[0,1] is L_c-Lipschitz with respect to the inferential divergence metric. If T_{k^*} induces (\delta,\eta)-semantic collapse and all other layers are admissible, then

\mathrm{CE}(h)\ge L_c\cdot\mu_{\mathcal{A}}(\mathcal{A}_\delta)\cdot(\delta-\eta)\cdot\prod_{j=k^*+1}^{n-1}\alpha_j,

where \mathcal{A}_\delta=\{a\in\mathcal{A}: \sqrt{D_{JS}(P_x(\cdot\mid a)\|P_y(\cdot\mid a))}>\delta/|\mathcal{A}|\} is the set of actions that can distinguish the collapsed pair.

Proof sketch. The collapsed pair (x,y) have outcome distributions that differ by at least \delta in inferential divergence but after transformation differ by at most \eta. For actions in \mathcal{A}_\delta, the actual outcome distributions under the original SI differ by more than \delta-\eta from those predicted by the collapsed representation. The Lipschitz property translates this divergence into a difference in confidence of at least L_c(\delta-\eta). The downstream contraction attenuates this difference by the product of later contraction factors. Taking expectation over actions yields the bound. ∎

2.7 Feedback Loop Stability

Definition 12 (Parameter Space). Let \Theta=(\theta_0,\dots,\theta_{n-1}) be the joint parameters of the CBA chain, with \Theta\in\Omega=\prod_k\Omega_k a Hilbert space.

Definition 13 (Feedback Update Rule). Given a loss \mathcal{L}:\Omega\to\mathbb{R}_{\ge0} derived from human feedback, define the regularized update:

\theta_{k,t+1}=\theta_{k,t}-\gamma\nabla_{\theta_k}\mathcal{L}(\Theta_t)-\lambda(\theta_{k,t}-\theta_k^*),

with learning rate \gamma>0, regularization \lambda>0, and reference parameters \theta_k^* (initial trained values).

Definition 14 (Lyapunov Function). V(\Theta)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\|\theta_k-\theta_k^*\|^2.

Lemma 2 (Feedback Stability). Assume: (i) \mathcal{L} is L-smooth; (ii) \|\nabla_{\theta_k}\mathcal{L}(\Theta)\|\le G for all \Theta,k; (iii) \lambda>\frac{\gamma L}{2}. Then

V(\Theta_{t+1})\le(1-2\lambda\gamma+\gamma^2L)V(\Theta_t)+\frac{\gamma^2G^2}{\lambda},

and the iterates converge to a ball of radius R^*=\frac{\gamma G^2}{\lambda(2\lambda-\gamma L)} around \Theta^*.

Proof. Standard Lyapunov analysis; the full expansion is given in the final text. ∎

Corollary 4 (Spectral Normalization). Enforcing spectral normalization on all layers bounds the Lipschitz constant L of \mathcal{L}. Choosing \lambda>\gamma L/2 then guarantees stability.

2.8 Metric Computability

Definition 15 (Empirical Metric Estimator). Draw N actions i.i.d. from \mu_{\mathcal{A}}, and for each action, M outcome samples to estimate distributions. Then

\hat{d}_{\mathcal{X}}(x,y)=\sqrt{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\widehat{D_{JS}}\big(P_x(\cdot\mid a_i),P_y(\cdot\mid a_i)\big)},

where \widehat{D_{JS}} is the empirical Jensen‑Shannon divergence.

Lemma 3 (Approximation Error Bound). Assume the symmetrized KL divergence (and hence JSD) is bounded by M_0. Then with probability at least 1-\delta,

|\hat{d}_{\mathcal{X}}(x,y)-d_{\mathcal{X}}(x,y)|\le \sqrt{M_0}\left(\frac{\log(2/\delta)}{2N}\right)^{1/4}.

Proof. The square root of the average JSD is Lipschitz in the average; applying Hoeffding to the bounded JSD estimates and using the Lipschitz property of the square root yields the bound. ∎

