3. The Architecture as a Mathematical Object

The CBA is instantiated as a four‑layer admissible chain:

\mathcal{S}\xrightarrow{T_0}\mathcal{X}_1\xrightarrow{T_1}\mathcal{X}_2\xrightarrow{T_2}\mathcal{X}_3\xrightarrow{T_3}\mathcal{H}.

· Layer 0 (\mathcal{S},d_{\mathcal{S}}): raw SI outputs, no transformation.
· Layer 1 (\mathcal{X}_1,d_1): structural reduction — space of invariant features, with h_{\mathcal{X}_1}<h_{\mathcal{S}}.
· Layer 2 (\mathcal{X}_2,d_2): semantic translation — space of human‑compatible concepts, with h_{\mathcal{X}_2}<h_{\mathcal{X}_1}.
· Layer 3 (\mathcal{X}_3,d_3): human interface — perceivable representations, with h_{\mathcal{X}_3}\le h_{\mathcal{X}_2}; must include explicit semantic uncertainty.
· Layer 4 (\mathcal{H},d_{\mathcal{H}}): human cognitive update (not engineerable, included for completeness).

Design constraints:

1. Choose \bar{\alpha}_k,\bar{\epsilon}_k and ensure \alpha_k\le\bar{\alpha}_k, \epsilon_k\le\bar{\epsilon}_k.
2. Verify entropy monotonicity.
3. Set \gamma,\lambda satisfying \lambda>\gamma L/2 via spectral normalization.

