5. Impossibility Results and Fundamental Limits

Theorem 3 (Existence of Admissible Chains). Let (\mathcal{S},d_{\mathcal{S}}) and (\mathcal{H},d_{\mathcal{H}}) be compact pragmatic semantic spaces with h_{\mathcal{S}}\ge h_{\mathcal{H}}. Let \Lambda^*\in(0,1) and \mathcal{E}^*>0 be given. Assume that for every \delta>0 there exists a \delta-net of \mathcal{S} such that each cell contains a representative whose action‑outcome model is within \epsilon of any point in the cell (a “quantization with bounded distortion” property). Then there exists an admissible CBA chain of depth n=\lceil h_{\mathcal{S}}/h_{\mathcal{H}}\rceil with \Lambda\le\Lambda^* and \mathcal{E}\le\mathcal{E}^*.

Proof. Construct spaces \mathcal{X}_k with entropies linearly interpolating from h_{\mathcal{S}} to h_{\mathcal{H}}. Define T_k as quantization onto a \delta_k-net, mapping each point to the representative of its cell. The contractivity factor is given by the ratio of entropies, and the distortion property ensures action‑consistency errors can be made arbitrarily small by choosing fine enough nets. Choosing depth and net sizes appropriately satisfies the bounds. ∎

Theorem 4 (Impossibility of Lossless Bridging). Let \mathcal{S},\mathcal{H} be compact pragmatic semantic spaces with h_{\mathcal{S}}>h_{\mathcal{H}}. For any CBA chain \Phi:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{H},

\mathrm{ED}(\Phi)<1,

and moreover

\inf_{\Phi}\mathrm{ED}(\Phi)\le\frac{h_{\mathcal{H}}}{h_{\mathcal{S}}}<1.

Proof. Because h_{\mathcal{S}}>h_{\mathcal{H}}, for sufficiently small \delta we have \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{S})>\mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{H}). Any map \Phi must send the \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{S}) points of a minimal \delta-net in \mathcal{S} into \mathcal{H}. By the pigeonhole principle, at least \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{S})-\mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{H}) pairs of distinct points collapse to the same image, so their inferential distance becomes zero while the original distance was at least \delta. Hence \mathrm{ED}(\Phi)\le 1-\delta' for some \delta'>0. Taking \delta\to 0 and using the definition of metric entropy, we obtain the upper bound \frac{h_{\mathcal{H}}}{h_{\mathcal{S}}}. ∎

