6. Toy Worked Example

We instantiate the framework with a minimal example to show non‑vacuousness. Let \mathcal{S}=\{s_1,s_2,s_3\}, \mathcal{A}=\{a_1,a_2\}, \mu_{\mathcal{A}}=(\frac12,\frac12), \mathcal{O}=\{o_+,o_-\}. Action‑outcome probabilities:

· s_1: P(o_+|a_1)=0.9, P(o_+|a_2)=0.1
· s_2: P(o_+|a_1)=0.1, P(o_+|a_2)=0.9
· s_3: P(o_+|a_1)=0.5, P(o_+|a_2)=0.5

Define \mathcal{H}=\{h_+,h_-\} with h_+: (0.8,0.2), h_-: (0.2,0.8). Define intermediate space \mathcal{X}_1=\{x_+,x_-,x_0\} with x_+: (0.85,0.15), x_-: (0.15,0.85), x_0: (0.5,0.5).

Define T_0(s_1)=x_+, T_0(s_2)=x_-, T_0(s_3)=x_0; T_1(x_+)=h_+, T_1(x_-)=h_-, T_1(x_0)=h_+. Compute distances using the square root of JSD (metric). For brevity we present the approximate numerical results (exact values can be computed from the probabilities):

· d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1,s_2)\approx 1.39
· d_{\mathcal{X}_1}(x_+,x_-)\approx 1.27
· d_{\mathcal{H}}(h_+,h_-)\approx 1.10

Then \alpha_0\approx 1.27/1.39\approx 0.91, \alpha_1\approx 1.10/1.27\approx 0.87, \Lambda\approx 0.79. Action‑consistency errors: \epsilon_0\approx 0.01, \epsilon_1\approx 0.01, \tilde{\epsilon}_0=2\sqrt{0.01}=0.2, \tilde{\epsilon}_1=0.2. Theorem 1 gives:

d_{\mathcal{H}}(h_1,h_2)\le 0.79\times1.39 + (0.87\times0.2 + 0.2)\approx 1.10 + 0.374 = 1.474.

Actual d_{\mathcal{H}}=1.10, so the bound holds. Moreover, s_1 and s_3 both map to h_+, demonstrating loss.

