7. Philosophical Foundations

Why inferentialism. Representationalist theories require access to the represented world‑states, which is impossible for arbitrary AI systems. Inferentialism (Brandom, 1994) grounds meaning in use: what inferences a representation licenses and what actions it supports. CBA’s metric captures exactly this: two representations are close if they support the same action‑outcome predictions.

Pragmatic sufficiency. CBA shifts the criterion from representational fidelity to pragmatic sufficiency: the human representation need not mirror the SI representation; it need only support correct action. Corollary 1 formalizes this: the bound is on inferential divergence — a measure of action‑outcome prediction quality — not on propositional content.

Structural coupling. Following Luhmann (1984), human and SI are operationally closed systems. Communication is structural coupling: each system selects from its environment what is relevant to its own operations. CBA designs a coupling medium; Theorem 1 bounds how much of the original structure survives.

Intelligence as relational property. A human‑CBA‑SI triad exhibits collective intelligence that neither the human nor the SI possesses alone. Theorem 1 quantifies how much of the SI’s contribution survives — a measure of collective intelligence.

