Appendix A: Full Proof of Theorem 1 (Semantic Convergence)

We restate Theorem 1 and provide a complete induction proof with explicit handling of the error accumulation.

Theorem 1 (Semantic Convergence). Let \{T_k\}_{k=0}^{n-1} be an admissible CBA chain where each T_k is \alpha_k-contractive and \epsilon_k-action‑consistent. Define \tilde{\epsilon}_k = 2\sqrt{\epsilon_k}. Then for any s_1, s_2 \in \mathcal{S}, with h_i = T_{n-1} \circ \cdots \circ T_0(s_i),

d_{\mathcal{H}}(h_1, h_2) \le \left(\prod_{k=0}^{n-1} \alpha_k\right) d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1, s_2) + \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} \left(\prod_{j=k+1}^{n-1} \alpha_j\right) \tilde{\epsilon}_k,

where empty products equal 1.

Proof. We proceed by strong induction on the chain depth n.

Base case n=1. Then \Phi = T_0. By Lemma 1 (Perturbed Contraction Composition) applied with \alpha = \alpha_0 and \epsilon = \epsilon_0,

d_{\mathcal{H}}(T_0(s_1), T_0(s_2)) \le \alpha_0 d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1, s_2) + 2\sqrt{\epsilon_0} = \alpha_0 d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1, s_2) + \tilde{\epsilon}_0.

This matches the formula with the product over an empty set of \alpha’s (i.e., 1) for the error term.

Inductive hypothesis. Assume the theorem holds for all admissible chains of depth m for any m \le n.

Inductive step for depth n+1. Consider an admissible chain of depth n+1: \mathcal{S} \xrightarrow{T_0} \mathcal{X}_1 \xrightarrow{T_1} \cdots \xrightarrow{T_{n-1}} \mathcal{X}_n \xrightarrow{T_n} \mathcal{H}. Define the intermediate points for i = 1,2:

x_k^{(i)} = T_{k-1} \circ \cdots \circ T_0(s_i), \quad k = 1,\dots,n.

Thus x_n^{(i)} is the output after the first n layers. The subchain T_0,\dots,T_{n-1} from \mathcal{S} to \mathcal{X}_n is admissible of depth n. By the induction hypothesis,

d_n(x_n^{(1)}, x_n^{(2)}) \le \left(\prod_{k=0}^{n-1} \alpha_k\right) d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1, s_2) + \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} \left(\prod_{j=k+1}^{n-1} \alpha_j\right) \tilde{\epsilon}_k. \tag{1}

Now apply Lemma 1 to the final transformation T_n : \mathcal{X}_n \to \mathcal{H}, which is \alpha_n-contractive and \epsilon_n-action‑consistent:

d_{\mathcal{H}}(h_1, h_2) = d_{\mathcal{H}}(T_n(x_n^{(1)}), T_n(x_n^{(2)})) \le \alpha_n \, d_n(x_n^{(1)}, x_n^{(2)}) + 2\sqrt{\epsilon_n} = \alpha_n \, d_n(x_n^{(1)}, x_n^{(2)}) + \tilde{\epsilon}_n. \tag{2}

Substitute (1) into (2):

d_{\mathcal{H}}(h_1, h_2) \le \alpha_n \left[ \left(\prod_{k=0}^{n-1} \alpha_k\right) d_{\mathcal{S}} + \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} \left(\prod_{j=k+1}^{n-1} \alpha_j\right) \tilde{\epsilon}_k \right] + \tilde{\epsilon}_n.

Simplify the product:

\alpha_n \prod_{k=0}^{n-1} \alpha_k = \prod_{k=0}^{n} \alpha_k.

For the error sum, each term \tilde{\epsilon}_k gets multiplied by \alpha_n \prod_{j=k+1}^{n-1} \alpha_j = \prod_{j=k+1}^{n} \alpha_j. Thus

d_{\mathcal{H}}(h_1, h_2) \le \left(\prod_{k=0}^{n} \alpha_k\right) d_{\mathcal{S}} + \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} \left(\prod_{j=k+1}^{n} \alpha_j\right) \tilde{\epsilon}_k + \tilde{\epsilon}_n.

The last term \tilde{\epsilon}_n can be written as \left(\prod_{j=n+1}^{n} \alpha_j\right) \tilde{\epsilon}_n with the empty product equal to 1. Hence the sum can be extended to k = n, yielding the desired formula for depth n+1:

d_{\mathcal{H}}(h_1, h_2) \le \left(\prod_{k=0}^{n} \alpha_k\right) d_{\mathcal{S}} + \sum_{k=0}^{n} \left(\prod_{j=k+1}^{n} \alpha_j\right) \tilde{\epsilon}_k.

This completes the induction, proving the theorem for all n \ge 1. ∎

