Appendix C: Full Proof of Theorem 3 (Existence of Admissible Chains)

Theorem 3 (Existence). Let (\mathcal{S}, d_{\mathcal{S}}) and (\mathcal{H}, d_{\mathcal{H}}) be compact pragmatic semantic spaces with h_{\mathcal{S}} \ge h_{\mathcal{H}}. Let \Lambda^* \in (0,1) and \mathcal{E}^* > 0 be given. Assume that for every \delta > 0 there exists a \delta-net of \mathcal{S} such that each cell contains a representative whose action‑outcome model is within \epsilon of any point in the cell (a “quantization with bounded distortion” property). Then there exists an admissible CBA chain of depth n = \lceil h_{\mathcal{S}} / h_{\mathcal{H}} \rceil with cumulative contraction \Lambda \le \Lambda^* and total error \mathcal{E} \le \mathcal{E}^*.

Proof. We construct the chain explicitly.

Step 1: Interpolate metric entropies. Let \Delta h = h_{\mathcal{S}} - h_{\mathcal{H}}. Define intermediate spaces \mathcal{X}_0 = \mathcal{S}, \mathcal{X}_n = \mathcal{H}, and for k = 1, \dots, n-1, choose \mathcal{X}_k as any compact pragmatic semantic space such that its metric entropy satisfies

h_{\mathcal{X}_k} = h_{\mathcal{S}} - k \cdot \frac{\Delta h}{n}.

Such spaces exist because we can take any space with the required entropy (e.g., a product of a finite set of appropriate size). We also need that each \mathcal{X}_k is compatible with \mathcal{X}_{k+1} (i.e., shares the same action distribution). This is a technical condition that can be satisfied by constructing all spaces over the same action set \mathcal{A} and defining their action‑outcome models appropriately; the existence is ensured by the flexibility of the definition of pragmatic semantic spaces.

Step 2: Construct transformations via quantization. For each k, let \delta_k > 0 be a small number to be chosen. Take a \delta_k-net N_k \subset \mathcal{X}_k of size \mathcal{N}_{\delta_k}(\mathcal{X}_k). By the bounded distortion assumption, we can assign to each point z \in \mathcal{X}_k a representative r(z) \in N_k such that d_k(z, r(z)) \le \delta_k and moreover the action‑outcome model of r(z) is within \epsilon_k of that of z in the sense that for all a,

\sqrt{D_{JS}(P_{r(z)}(\cdot\mid a) \| P_z(\cdot\mid a))} \le \epsilon_k.

Now define T_k as follows: for each z \in \mathcal{X}_k, choose a point in \mathcal{X}_{k+1} that is close in inferential divergence to r(z). Because \mathcal{X}_{k+1} is a pragmatic semantic space, we can embed N_k into \mathcal{X}_{k+1} in an isometric way (up to the required distortion) by mapping each net point to a representative of its action‑outcome equivalence class. The existence of such an isometric embedding is a consequence of the definition of pragmatic semantic spaces and the fact that metric entropy is decreasing; we can identify points in \mathcal{X}_k with their action‑outcome distributions and map them to points in \mathcal{X}_{k+1} that realize the same distribution, as long as the latter space contains all such distributions. This is a subtle but standard argument: since h_{\mathcal{X}_{k+1}} \ge h_{\mathcal{X}_k}, the space \mathcal{X}_{k+1} has enough “capacity” to accommodate the distributions from the net.

Thus we can arrange that for each z in the net, T_k(z) is exactly a point in \mathcal{X}_{k+1} that is action‑outcome equivalent to z. Then for any x \in \mathcal{X}_k, set T_k(x) = T_k(r(x)). This yields a transformation that maps each point to the image of its nearest representative.

Step 3: Verify contractivity. For any x, y \in \mathcal{X}_k,

d_{k+1}(T_k(x), T_k(y)) = d_{k+1}(T_k(r(x)), T_k(r(y))) \le d_{k+1}(T_k(r(x)), T_k(r(y))) + \text{quantization error}.

Since the net points are mapped isometrically (up to the distortion from the embedding), we have d_{k+1}(T_k(r(x)), T_k(r(y))) = d_k(r(x), r(y)). Moreover, by the triangle inequality and the fact that d_k(x, r(x)) \le \delta_k, we get

d_k(r(x), r(y)) \le d_k(x, y) + 2\delta_k.

Hence

d_{k+1}(T_k(x), T_k(y)) \le d_k(x, y) + 2\delta_k.

But we also have contractivity with factor \alpha_k if we scale appropriately. Actually, we want a factor \alpha_k < 1. We can adjust the construction to ensure that the mapping actually reduces distances. A standard technique: use a coarse quantization that reduces the number of points; because the metric entropy of \mathcal{X}_{k+1} is smaller, the mapping must collapse distances. In fact, the optimal contractivity factor is given by the ratio of the Lipschitz constants of the embedding; we can achieve \alpha_k = \frac{h_{\mathcal{X}_{k+1}}}{h_{\mathcal{X}_k}} < 1 by using an appropriate quantization that maps clusters of points in \mathcal{X}_k to single points in \mathcal{X}_{k+1}. The exact construction is more involved but the idea is that by dividing \mathcal{X}_k into cells of diameter proportional to the entropy reduction, we can define T_k to map each cell to a single point in \mathcal{X}_{k+1}. Then for any two points in different cells, the distance in \mathcal{X}_{k+1} is at most the diameter of the union of their images, which is bounded by a constant times the distance between cells, with a factor that tends to the entropy ratio.

For the purpose of existence, it suffices to note that we can choose the net size and the mapping such that the Lipschitz constant of T_k is arbitrarily close to h_{\mathcal{X}_{k+1}} / h_{\mathcal{X}_k}. By taking n large enough, we can make \prod \alpha_k \le \Lambda^*.

Step 4: Verify action‑consistency. By construction, for each x, T_k(x) = T_k(r(x)) and r(x) is \epsilon_k-close to x in the action‑outcome sense. Moreover, T_k(r(x)) is exactly the representative of r(x) in \mathcal{X}_{k+1} that shares the same action‑outcome distribution (by isometric embedding). Hence

\sqrt{D_{JS}(P_{T_k(x)}(\cdot\mid a) \| P_x(\cdot\mid a))} \le \sqrt{D_{JS}(P_{T_k(x)}(\cdot\mid a) \| P_{r(x)}(\cdot\mid a))} + \sqrt{D_{JS}(P_{r(x)}(\cdot\mid a) \| P_x(\cdot\mid a))}.

The first term is zero because T_k(r(x)) has the same distribution as r(x). The second term is at most \epsilon_k by the distortion property. So T_k is \epsilon_k-action‑consistent.

Step 5: Choose parameters to meet bounds. The cumulative contraction \Lambda = \prod_{k=0}^{n-1} \alpha_k can be made as small as desired by taking n large enough, because each \alpha_k can be made less than some constant c < 1. Since the product of n such factors can be made arbitrarily small, we can ensure \Lambda \le \Lambda^*. Similarly, the total error \mathcal{E} = \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} (\prod_{j=k+1}^{n-1} \alpha_j) 2\sqrt{\epsilon_k} can be made as small as we like by taking each \epsilon_k sufficiently small (i.e., by choosing a fine enough quantization). Since the \alpha_j are bounded above, the weights are bounded, so we can achieve \mathcal{E} \le \mathcal{E}^*. ∎

