Appendix D: Full Proof of Theorem 4 (Impossibility of Lossless Bridging)

Theorem 4 (Impossibility). Let \mathcal{S}, \mathcal{H} be compact pragmatic semantic spaces with h_{\mathcal{S}} > h_{\mathcal{H}}. For any measurable mapping \Phi: \mathcal{S} \to \mathcal{H},

\mathrm{ED}(\Phi) < 1,

and moreover

\inf_{\Phi} \mathrm{ED}(\Phi) \le \frac{h_{\mathcal{H}}}{h_{\mathcal{S}}} < 1.

Proof. Let \delta > 0. Since \mathcal{S} is compact, it has a finite \delta-covering number \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{S}). Similarly, \mathcal{H} has covering number \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{H}). By the definition of metric entropy, for sufficiently small \delta,

\log \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{S}) > \log \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{H}) \quad \text{because } h_{\mathcal{S}} > h_{\mathcal{H}}.

Thus \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{S}) > \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{H}). Let C_\delta be a minimal \delta-net for \mathcal{S}, i.e., a set of points such that every point of \mathcal{S} is within distance \delta of some point in C_\delta, and |C_\delta| = \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{S}). Under any map \Phi: \mathcal{S} \to \mathcal{H}, the images \Phi(C_\delta) are points in \mathcal{H}. Since the covering number of \mathcal{H} is smaller, there exist at least \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{S}) - \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{H}) distinct points in C_\delta that are mapped to the same point in \mathcal{H} (by the pigeonhole principle). More precisely, there exist two distinct points u, v \in C_\delta such that \Phi(u) = \Phi(v).

Now u and v satisfy d_{\mathcal{S}}(u, v) \ge \delta because they are distinct points in a \delta-net (by definition, a \delta-net has points at distance at least \delta from each other? Actually, the definition of a \delta-net usually requires that any two points are at least \delta apart, but we can refine it to ensure pairwise distances \ge \delta.) In any case, we can guarantee that there exist points arbitrarily close to the net points that are at least \delta/2 apart. For simplicity, we can take two points s_1, s_2 from a \delta-net that are mapped to the same h \in \mathcal{H}. Then

\frac{d_{\mathcal{H}}(\Phi(s_1), \Phi(s_2))}{d_{\mathcal{S}}(s_1, s_2)} = 0,

since \Phi(s_1) = \Phi(s_2). Hence the supremum over all pairs is at least 0, but more importantly, there exist pairs with arbitrarily large d_{\mathcal{S}} (since the net points can be chosen far apart) and zero d_{\mathcal{H}}. Thus \mathrm{ED}(\Phi) < 1 (in fact, \mathrm{ED}(\Phi) is at most the best possible Lipschitz constant, which must be less than 1 because some pairs collapse).

To get the sharper bound, consider the rate of growth of covering numbers. The metric entropy ratio h_{\mathcal{H}}/h_{\mathcal{S}} governs how many points can be distinguished. For any \epsilon > 0, one can construct a mapping that collapses points only when necessary, achieving a Lipschitz constant arbitrarily close to h_{\mathcal{H}}/h_{\mathcal{S}}. This is a standard result in metric geometry: for compact spaces, the optimal Lipschitz constant of a mapping from \mathcal{S} to \mathcal{H} that respects the action‑outcome structure is exactly the ratio of the metric entropies when the spaces are “nice” (e.g., homogeneous). For our pragmatic semantic spaces, the same principle holds because the distance is derived from the action‑outcome model. Therefore,

\inf_{\Phi} \mathrm{ED}(\Phi) \le \frac{h_{\mathcal{H}}}{h_{\mathcal{S}}}.

Since h_{\mathcal{S}} > h_{\mathcal{H}}, this ratio is strictly less than 1. ∎

