Appendix F: Metric Properties of the Square Root of Jensen‑Shannon Divergence

Proposition F.1. For probability distributions P and Q on a finite set, the square root of the Jensen‑Shannon divergence, \sqrt{D_{JS}(P\|Q)}, is a metric on the space of probability distributions.

Proof. Jensen‑Shannon divergence is defined as

D_{JS}(P\|Q) = \frac12 D_{KL}\!\left(P \;\middle\|\; \frac{P+Q}{2}\right) + \frac12 D_{KL}\!\left(Q \;\middle\|\; \frac{P+Q}{2}\right).

It is known that \sqrt{D_{JS}} satisfies the triangle inequality because it is the Euclidean distance between the vectors of square roots of probabilities after a suitable transformation (see Endres and Schindelin, 2003). In particular, there exists an embedding of probability distributions into a Hilbert space such that the Euclidean distance equals \sqrt{D_{JS}}. Hence the triangle inequality holds. Symmetry and non‑negativity are immediate from the definition. The identity of indiscernibles follows from the fact that D_{JS}(P\|Q)=0 iff P=Q almost everywhere. ∎

Corollary F.2. The inferential divergence metric d_{\mathcal{X}}(x,y) = \sqrt{\mathbb{E}_{a\sim\mu_{\mathcal{A}}}\big[ D_{JS}(P_x(\cdot\mid a) \| P_y(\cdot\mid a)) \big]} is a metric on the space of equivalence classes of representations where two representations are identified if they induce the same action‑outcome distributions.

Proof. The expectation of a metric (the square root of JSD) is a metric, because for any metric \rho, the function \sqrt{\mathbb{E}[\rho^2]} is a metric (by Minkowski’s inequality). More directly, the mapping x \mapsto (a \mapsto \sqrt{P_x(\cdot\mid a)}) embeds the space into L^2(\mathcal{A} \times \mathcal{O}); the Euclidean distance in that space is exactly d_{\mathcal{X}}. Hence d_{\mathcal{X}} inherits the properties of a metric. ∎

