Appendix G: Technical Lemmas on Covering Numbers and Metric Entropy

Lemma G.1 (Covering number monotonicity). If (\mathcal{X}, d_{\mathcal{X}}) and (\mathcal{Y}, d_{\mathcal{Y}}) are metric spaces with h_{\mathcal{X}} > h_{\mathcal{Y}}, then for sufficiently small \delta, \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{X}) > \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{Y}).

Proof. By definition, h_{\mathcal{X}} = \lim_{\delta\to0} \log \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{X}) / \log(1/\delta). If h_{\mathcal{X}} > h_{\mathcal{Y}}, then there exists \delta_0 such that for all \delta < \delta_0,

\frac{\log \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{X})}{\log(1/\delta)} > \frac{\log \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{Y})}{\log(1/\delta)}.

Multiplying by \log(1/\delta) > 0 yields \log \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{X}) > \log \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{Y}), hence \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{X}) > \mathcal{N}_\delta(\mathcal{Y}). ∎

Lemma G.2 (Quantization distortion). For any compact metric space (\mathcal{X}, d) and any \epsilon > 0, there exists a finite set N \subset \mathcal{X} (an \epsilon-net) such that every point of \mathcal{X} is within distance \epsilon of some point in N. Moreover, for each point x, there exists a representative r(x) \in N such that d(x, r(x)) \le \epsilon.

Proof. This is a standard result in topology: compactness implies total boundedness, so for any \epsilon we can cover \mathcal{X} with finitely many balls of radius \epsilon. Choose the centers as the net. ∎

